COMP7270 Web and Mobile Programming & COMP7980 Dynamic Web and Mobile Programming - HKBU - Spring2025

Today, we will cover building an interactive web application with Vue 3, Oruga UI components, and ApexCharts for data visualization. Core techniques and concepts covered include:

  • Consuming API data with Oruga's out-of-the-box components
  • Implementing client-side filtering and pagination
  • Using ApexCharts components to visualize data
  • Creating and aggregating data with a MongoDB backend
  • Passing props between components for reusability

Download the two zip files from last week, and start them with two VSCode windows.

Part 1. The Bookings Page

Let's first set up a new route in /router/index.js:

{
  path: '/bookings',
  name: 'view-bookings',
  // route level code-splitting
  // this generates a separate chunk (about.[hash].js) for this route
  // which is lazy-loaded when the route is visited.

Then, create a new file BookingsView.vue under folder views.

Oruga

When building tables and paginations in Vue.js, we have the option to utilize Vue directives. However, there are also several useful Vue components available that can simplify the process. One such component library is Oruga.

Importing Oruga

To import and use Oruga in your Vue.js project, follow the instructions below:

In your terminal, run the following commands to install Oruga and its Bootstrap theme:

npm install @oruga-ui/oruga-next
npm install @oruga-ui/theme-bootstrap

To enable pagination icons using Material icons, run the following command.

npm i @mdi/font

In your main.js file, import and configure Oruga and the icons as shown:

import './assets/main.css'

import { createApp } from 'vue'
import App from './App.vue'
import router from './router'
import Oruga from '@oruga-ui/oruga-next';

import { bootstrapConfig } from '@oruga-ui/theme-bootstrap';

import '@oruga-ui/theme-bootstrap/dist/bootstrap.css';
import '@mdi/font/css/materialdesignicons.min.css';

// import 'bootstrap/dist/css/bootstrap.css'
import "bootstrap"

const app = createApp(App)

app.use(router).use(Oruga, bootstrapConfig)

app.mount('#app')

Oruga Paginated Table

  1. Visit the Oruga Table documentation page at https://oruga-ui.com/components/Table.html.
  2. Locate the code sections labeled HTML within the Async Data section.
  3. Copy and paste the following JS and abovementioned HTML code into the <script setup> section and the <template> section in the BookingsView.vue.
import { ref, onMounted } from "vue";

const data = ref([]);
const total = ref(0);
const loading = ref(false);
const sortField = ref("");
const sortOrder = ref("desc");
const page = ref(1);
const perPage = ref(20);

const loadAsyncData = () => {
  const params = [
    "api_key=bb6f51bef07465653c3e553d6ab161a8",
    "language=en-US",
    "include_adult=false",
    "include_video=false",
    `sort_by=${sortField.value}.${sortOrder.value}`,
    `page=${page.value}`,
  ].join("&");
  loading.value = true;
  fetch(`https://api.themoviedb.org/3/discover/movie?${params}`)
    .then((response) => response.json())
    .then((result) => {
      // api.themoviedb.org manage max 1000 pages
      let currentTotal = result.total_results;
      if (result.total_results / perPage.value > 100)
        currentTotal = perPage.value * 100;

      total.value = currentTotal;
      data.value = result.results.map((item) => {
        item.release_date = item.release_date
          ? item.release_date.replace(/-/g, "/")
          : null;
        return item;
      });
      // cap results for usability
      if (data.value.length > 10) data.value = data.value.slice(0, 5);
      loading.value = false;
    })
    .catch((error) => {
      data.value = [];
      total.value = 0;
      loading.value = false;
      throw error;
    });
};

/*
 * Handle page-change event
 */
const onPageChange = (p) => {
  page.value = p;
  loadAsyncData();
};

/*
 * Handle sort event
 */
const onSort = (column, order) => {
  sortField.value = column.field;
  sortOrder.value = order;
  loadAsyncData();
};

/*
 * Type style in relation to the value
 */
const type = (value) => {
  const number = parseFloat(value);
  if (number < 6) {
    return "is-danger";
  } else if (number >= 6 && number < 8) {
    return "is-warning";
  } else if (number >= 8) {
    return "is-success";
  }
};

onMounted(() => {
  loadAsyncData();
});

Sorting

Let's uncomment the following line in the params:

// `sort_by=${sortField.value}.${sortOrder.value}`,

Now, we will allow sorting according to the numTickets value.

Clicking the field title will generate a request as follows in the terminal of the backend:

GET /bookings?sort_by=numTickets.desc&page=1

To handle this sorting in the backend, inside bookings.js, let's modify the / route router.get('/', async function (req, res) {} from

let result = await db.collection("bookings").find(query).skip(skip).limit(perPage).toArray();

to as follows:

// sort by sort_by query parameter
let sort = {};
if (req.query.sort_by) {

	// split the sort_by into an array
	let sortBy = req.query.sort_by.split(".");

	// check if the first element is a valid field
	if (sortBy.length > 1 && ["numTickets"].includes(sortBy[0])) {
		sort[sortBy[0]] = sortBy[1] == "desc" ? -1 : 1;
	}
}

let result = await db.collection("bookings").find(query).sort(sort).skip(skip).limit(perPage).toArray();

Search Box

Our table can also support searching. Create a new input field above the table that allows users to search for specific bookings by email.

<input class="form-control" v-model="search" placeholder="Search..." />

Watcher

To implement the watcher functionality for the search value and trigger the loadAsyncData() function when the search value changes, follow these steps:

  1. Define a reactive variable called search using the ref() function.
  2. Set up a watcher using the watch() function, which watches for changes in the search.value.
  3. Inside the watcher's callback function, call the loadAsyncData() function.
import { ref, onMounted, watch } from "vue" // add watch

const search = ref("");

watch(() => search.value, () => {
    loadAsyncData();
});

Inside the fetch() function, add `email=${search.value}` to params.

Router Link

In a Vue application, when using RouterLink elements to create links, you can modify {{ props.row.email }} to include a RouterLink with the appropriate to attribute. This will ensure that the link directs the user to the booking view page.

Replace {{ row.email }} with the following code:

<RouterLink :to="`/booking/${row._id}`"> {{ row.email }} </RouterLink>

Part 2. Interactive Charts with ApexChart

Among major chart libraries on the market, ApexChart has the best integration with modern frontend frameworks like Vue (https://apexcharts.com/docs/vue-charts/).

To install ApexCharts for Vue 3, you can run the following lines in the terminal:

npm install --save apexcharts
npm install --save vue3-apexcharts

By executing these commands, you'll install the ApexCharts library and the Vue 3 wrapper for ApexCharts called vue3-apexcharts.

To import ApexCharts globally in main.js and make it available throughout your Vue 3 application, you need to make the following modifications.

import VueApexCharts from "vue3-apexcharts";

app.use(router).use(Oruga, bootstrapConfig).use(VueApexCharts)

Component

We will create a chart component based on the Donut chart example from the official ApexCharts documentation for Vue. However, the original code is written using the Options API, and we would like to use the Composition API instead. Therefore, we need to make some slight changes to adapt the code.

Let's create a Vue file called /components/DonutChart.vue to implement this component. The code for the component will be as follows:

<script setup>
import { ref } from "vue";

const options = ref({});
const series = ref([44, 55, 41, 17, 15]);
</script>

<template>
    <div>
        <apexchart type="donut" :options="options" :series="series" />
    </div>
</template>

Aggregate in MongoDB

To display the superhero popularities on the chart, we can retrieve the necessary data through a MongoDB operation. Let's navigate to our Express application and create a new route handler in routes/bookings.js:

// Get the total number of bookings per superhero
router.get('/stats/superhero', async function (req, res) {
    const db = await connectToDB();
    try {
        let result = await db.collection("bookings").aggregate([
            // non null superhero
            { $match: { superhero: { $ne: null } } },
            { $group: { _id: "$superhero", total: { $sum: 1 } } }
        ]).toArray();

        res.json(result);
    } catch (err) {
        res.status(400).json({ message: err.message });
    } finally {
        await db.client.close();
    }
});

MongoDB provides the aggregate() method, which allows us to perform more complex operations using a pipeline consisting of multiple stages.

In the above code, we use the aggregate() method with a pipeline consisting of two stages. The first $match stage filters out bookings with invalid superhero values. The second stage utilizes $group to group the remaining documents based on the superhero field. By using $sum, we calculate the total popularity for each superhero.

Once you restart the Express application, you can access this data via the following URL: http://localhost:3000/bookings/stats/superhero

Consuming this API

Back in the DonutChart.vue file, let's implement the following onMounted function to consume the API:

import { ref, onMounted } from "vue";

const options = ref({});
const series = ref([]);

onMounted(async () => {
    var response = await fetch("/api/bookings/stats/superhero");
    var json = await response.json();
    options.value = { labels: json.map((item) => item._id) };
    series.value = json.map((item) => item.total);
});

Using the map() method on the json array, we extract the _id property from each superhero object and assign it to the labels property of the options object. Similarly, we extract the total property and assign it to the series array.

By doing this, we populate the necessary data for the chart to display the superhero popularities.

Filter

We can modify the route as follows:

try {
	let pipelines = [];

	if (req.query.team) {
		pipelines.push({ $match: { team: req.query.team } });
	}

	pipelines = pipelines.concat([
		// non null superhero
		{ $match: { superhero: { $ne: null } } },
		{ $group: { _id: "$superhero", total: { $sum: 1 } } }
	]);

	let result = await db.collection("bookings").aggregate(pipelines).toArray();
	res.json(result);
}

In this updated code, we first check if the team query parameter is provided. If it is, we add a $match stage to the pipelines array to filter documents based on the team field.

After that, we continue with the remaining stages: filtering out bookings with invalid superhero values and grouping the remaining documents based on the superhero field to calculate the total popularity.

Props

In the context of Vue.js, props are a way to pass data from a parent component to its child component. The child component receives the prop values and can use them within its template, computed properties, or methods.

Props are generally used to make components more reusable and flexible by allowing the parent component to pass dynamic data to the child component. This enables the child component to adapt its behavior and appearance based on the values received through props.

Props are defined using the defineProps() function from the Vue Composition API. The defineProps() function allows us to explicitly define the props that the component expects to receive from its parent component.

<script setup>
import { ref, onMounted, defineProps } from "vue";

const props = defineProps({
    team: String,
});

const options = ref({});
const series = ref([]);

onMounted(async () => {
    var response = await fetch("/api/bookings/stats/superhero?team=" + props.team);
    var json = await response.json();
    options.value = {
        labels: json.map((item) => item._id),
        title: { text: props.team || "All Teams" }
    };
    series.value = json.map((item) => item.total);
});
</script>

In our case, the component expects a prop named team of type String. By defining the prop using defineProps(), we are explicitly stating that the component requires the team prop to be passed from its parent component.

Within the component, the props object can be accessed to retrieve the values passed from the parent component. In the provided code snippet, the team prop is used in the fetch() request to dynamically filter the superhero statistics based on the team.

Additionally, the props object is used to set the title property of the options object, which is used for the chart. If the team prop is provided, it is used as the title text; otherwise, "All Teams" is used as the default text.
